statement:
Determine, with explanation, whether the improper integral

\begin{align*}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}\frac{x}{x^{2}+1}\,dx\end{align*}

converges or diverges.

sols:
The integral is equal to the sum of the two standard Type I integrals:

\begin{align*}\int_{-\infty}^0\frac{x}{x^2+1}dx+\int_0^\infty\frac{x}{x^2+1}dx.\end{align*}

By the substitution \emph{u}=\emph{x}\textsuperscript{2}+1, \emph{du} =
2\emph{dx}, we see that

\begin{align*}
\int \frac{x}{x^2+1} dx &= \frac{1}{2} \int \frac{1}{u}du \\
&= \frac{1}{2}\ln|u|+C \\
&= \frac{1}{2}\ln|x^2+1|+C \end{align*}

So, we calculate

\begin{align*}
\int_0^\infty\frac{x}{x^2+1}dx &= \lim_{a\to \infty}\frac{1}{2}\ln(x^2+1)\big|_0^a \\
&=\lim_{a\to \infty}(\frac{1}{2}\ln(a^2+1)-\ln(1)) \\
&=\infty\end{align*}

Since this part diverges the whole integral diverges also.
